huntYears.NOTES: Desert unit with low deer densities.

huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION:
Most hunters plan on spending at least 3-4 days hunting.  There are few water sources so plan on bringing extra water in with you. Foot hunters who plan to hunt in the upper elevations should plan on staying up there for several days. It is just too far to come down every day.  I would plan on a very challenging and rewarding hunt. Review your maps frequently to avoid trespass issues on the Goshutes.

This area is patrolled quite frequently by DWR and BLM personnel.  Keep this in mind when you are transporting your game and driving an ATV.  Try to make it easy to access the permit and tag on the animal.
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS: This is a very remote location with limited access.  Cellular phones will not work.  Digital cell phones may show a bar but will not connect due to the distance to the cell towers.  Satellite phones do work in the area.  The Biologist suggests handheld radios and even a "Spot Tracker" type of satellite messaging device for safety.  Make sure someone knows where you plan to camp and when you will return. Bring an extra spare tire, water and gas. There are not facilities. Wendover is the closest (60 miles).
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically during the hunting season.  Be prepared for rain, lightening, snow, wind and heat.  Thunder storms can cause muddy road conditions and flash floods in this region.  Most hunters struggle with meat spoiling in the heat.  I would plan on hot weather and plan accordingly.
huntBios.MANAGEMENT_OBJ: 32.5~11200 (entire West Desert unit)~7000 (entire West Desert unit)~15–17~23.6~~~~~~~~For more detailed information on population and objective data please see the Big Game Annual Report Page.
huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
This unit has a low deer population and is very remote with extreme topography. This is a very difficult unit to find deer. If you never have seen the Deep Creeks you better go look before your hunt. A good spotting scope and binoculars are essential for scouting deer in this area. Scouting is most effective mid-summer. If you are able to place trail cameras on the remote springs and water holes you will be able to pattern the movements of the bucks along with everyone else. This is a popular unit to put cameras out. In the hot early fall temperatures I would expect to see the most animals at prime time (1/2 hour before dawn and an hour before sunset)unless pressured.
Upper elevations deer spend a lot of time in the aspen patches where there is a good understory of grass and forbs. I would bring a good map, compass, GPS, and if possible someone who is familiar with the area. Consult with the Goshute Reservation for info on the reservation boundaries. The reservation expanded a few years ago and the public maps are not up to date. If you have never set foot in this unit, it might appear small on a map but on the ground it is quite a large area.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: The majority of land is managed by BLM and private ownership. The majority of the unit is a Wilderness Study Area administered by both Salt Lake and Filmore  BLM Field Offices. The southern and south east part of the Deep creek Mts. is Owned and control by Goshute Indian Reservation out of Ibapah, Utah.
huntBoundaryInfos.WMA_IN_UNIT: There are no State WMA in this area. There is Fish Spring National Refuge which does not allow big game hunting.
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:
There are many dispersed camping sites within this unit. Please direct all questions regarding roads, maps and camping to the BLM Fillmore or Salt Lake Field Offices.
Salt Lake BLM Field Office - BLM - https://www.blm.gov/utah
Salt Lake Field Office 2370 S. Decker Lake Blvd West Valley City, UT 84119 (801) 320-8300
Bureau of Land Management Fillmore Field Office 95 East 500 North Fillmore, Utah 84631 Phone: (435) 743-3100 Fax: (435) 743-3135
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIM_ACCESS_PTS:
Pony Express road, Brush Wellman Hwy(IPP), SR 50/6, Nevada 93,
Deep Creek and Cedar Mts.- The mountain is a Wilderness Study Area. This area has strict travel constraints. There are a handful of roads which will allow vehicular travel. Consult the BLM for a list of those roads. It is for the most part limited to horse and foot travel. No vehicle access is permitted in these areas. The mountain should be considered rough and primitive. There are only a few trails.
huntBoundaryInfos.SUGGESTED_MAPS: Suggested Maps: BLM:  Fish Springs, Wildcat Mountain,Tule Valley,Tooele 1:100,000. Consult the the Goshutes for the latest tribal lands map.
huntBoundaryInfos.COUNTY_ROAD_INFO: Most of the roads in this unit are improved gravel. However it is not uncommon to have thunderstorms, flash floods and have roads and trails wash out.  If it rains hard it makes it difficult to navigate and road and trails get very slick
huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS: Notice: Deep Creek Mtns and Cedar Mtns are Wilderness Study Areas, all motorized vehicles and travel are restricted in these areas.
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES: Goshute Tribal Lands are excluded from this unit.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Juab, Millard and Tooele counties—Boundary begins at the Utah-Nevada state line and I-80 in Wendover; east on I-80 to Exit 77 and SR-196; south on SR-196 to Government Creek Road near Dugway; south on this road to the Pony Express Road: southwest on this road to 14-mile road (Dugway Valley road); south on this road to SR-174; east on SR-174 to US-6; south on US-6 to US-6/50; west on US-6/50 to the Utah Nevada state line; north on this state line to I-80 in Wendover. EXCLUDES ALL NATIVE AMERICAN TRUST LANDS WITHIN THIS BOUNDARY. Excludes all CWMUs. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Bonneville Salt Flat, Currie, Delta, Ely, Fish Springs, Kern Mountains, Lynndyl, Rush Valley, Tooele, Tule Valley, Wildcat Mountain. Boundary questions? Call the Springville office, 801-491-5678 or the Cedar City office, 435-865-6100.
